<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-09-25T12:29:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-09-25T12:29:00-05:00" n="29" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d29">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">837.00/1769: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Long</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Habana</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-09-25T12:00:00-05:29"><hi rend="italic">September
                                            25, 1920—noon</hi></date>.<lb/>[Received 6:45
                                    p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>227. Department’s telegram 167, September 23rd, 4 p.m. Request for
                                additional marines Camaguey based on necessity for protection sugar
                                interest owned by Americans in four eastern provinces. It is
                                estimated that a considerable percentage of total sugar production
                                of 1920 crop controlled by American interests. English, Spanish and
                                other foreign interests are also important. It is openly stated by
                                partisans of both parties that in event of revolution or other
                                disturbances American interests will be first to be destroyed.</p>
                            <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Long</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>